    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-09T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-09T18:00:00-05:00" n="268"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d268">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 657.119/387a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schmedeman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-09T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 9, 1918—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>255. At request of Doctor <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_NF1"
                        >Nansen</persName> War Trade Board have issued export licenses to Norwegian
                    Food Commission for shipment via <pb facs="0316" n="1150" xml:id="pg_1150"/>
                    S.S. <hi rend="italic">Bergensfjord</hi> sailing March 9 covering approximately
                    156 tons of seeds destined for spring planting in Norway. The War Trade Board
                    have given the question of the issuance of those licenses very careful thought
                    and have caused them to be issued because of political and other considerations,
                    particularly the imminence of the conclusion of this country’s agreement with
                    Norway and because no other sailings after March 9 were sufficiently
                    proximate.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
